  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "Loops",
      "name": "Lesson 1: Loops",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can the problem-solving process help me plan and implement an algorithm?**\n\nStudents are introduced to iteration using `while` loops to repeat instructions as long as a condition is `true`. Students discover that `while` loops can be combined with methods in the `Painter` class to allow them to repeat a block of code as long as a `Painter` object can move forward in the direction it is facing, is on a paint bucket, or has paint. They learn about the problem solving process and how this approach can help them break down a problem into manageable tasks and practice developing and implementing algorithms using sequencing and iteration in Java.",
        "preparation": "* Print copies of the Writing Algorithms handout (one for each student)\n* Preview the *While Loops* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can the problem-solving process help me plan and implement an algorithm?**\n\nIn this lesson, you are introduced to iteration using `while` loops to repeat instructions as long as a condition is `true`. You discover that `while` loops can be combined with methods in the `Painter` class to allow you to repeat a block of code as long as a `Painter` object can move forward in the direction it is facing, is on a paint bucket, or has paint. You learn about the problem solving process and how this approach can help you break down a problem into manageable tasks and practice developing and implementing algorithms using sequencing and iteration in Java."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Loops",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Selection Statements",
      "name": "Lesson 2: Selection Statements",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I write algorithms using sequencing, selection, and iteration in Java?**\n\nStudents have learned how to implement algorithms in Java that repeat a set of instructions while a condition is `true`. In this lesson, students explore selection and learn how to write algorithms using sequencing, selection, and iteration. Students discover additional methods in the `Painter` class that they can use in their algorithms to allow their `Painter` objects to make better decisions about which direction to move or turn or whether or not to paint. Students then practice writing algorithms using these components and methods while revisiting inheritance to create a subclass of the `PainterPlus` class.",
        "preparation": "* Print copies of the Investigate: Selection Statements handout (one for each pair of students)\n* Print copies of the Writing Algorithms handout (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Conditional Statements* video\n* Gather index cards or scrap pieces of paper (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can I write algorithms using sequencing, selection, and iteration in Java?**\n\nYou have learned how to implement algorithms in Java that repeat a set of instructions while a condition is `true`. In this lesson, you explore selection and learn how to write algorithms using sequencing, selection, and iteration. You discover additional methods in the `Painter` class that you can use in your algorithms to allow your `Painter` objects to make better decisions about which direction to move or turn or whether or not to paint. You then practice writing algorithms using these components and methods while revisiting inheritance to create a subclass of the `PainterPlus` class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Selection Statements",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Two-Way Selection Statements",
      "name": "Lesson 3: Two-Way Selection Statements",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I check if a condition is NOT `true` or execute a separate block of code if the condition is `false`?**\n\nStudents expand their knowledge of selection statements and Boolean values to learn how to use two-way selection statements and the NOT ( `!` ) logical operator. Students explore the functionality of two-way selection statements and the NOT ( `!` ) logical operator and consider how these can be used to expand or improve the algorithms they have developed so far. Students then practice using these to develop algorithms and create a new subclass of the `PainterPlus` class.",
        "preparation": "* Print copies of the Investigate: Selection and Logic handout (one for each pair of students)\n* Preview the *Two-Way Selection and NOT* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can I check if a condition is NOT `true` or execute a separate block of code if the condition is `false`?**\n\nSo far, you have used selection statements and Boolean values to execute a specific block of code if a condition is true. In this lesson, you learn how to use two-way selection statements and the NOT ( `!` ) logical operator. You explore the functionality of two-way selection statements and the NOT ( `!` ) logical operator and consider how these can be used to expand or improve the algorithms you have developed so far. You then practice using these to develop algorithms and create a new subclass of the `PainterPlus` class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Two-Way Selection Statements",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Object Aliases and Equality",
      "name": "Lesson 4: Object Aliases and Equality",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I check if two objects are equal?**\n\nIn this lesson, students discover the difference between comparing primitive values and object references. Students learn that two object references are considered aliases when they both reference the same object and how to identify aliases or `null` values using the `==` and `!=` operators. They revisit the `Object` class and learn how to override the `equals()` method to determine whether two instances of a class are equivalent. Students then practice overriding the `equals()` method in a class and comparing objects for equality.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Aliasing* and *The equals() Method* videos",
        "student_overview": "**How can I check if two objects are equal?**\n\nIn this lesson, you discover the difference between comparing primitive values and object references. You learn that two object references are considered aliases when they both reference the same object and how to identify aliases or `null` values using the `==` and `!=` operators. You revisit the `Object` class and learn how to override the `equals()` method to determine whether two instances of a class are equivalent. You then practice overriding the `equals()` method in a class and comparing objects for equality."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Object Aliases and Equality",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Nested If Statements",
      "name": "Lesson 5: Nested If Statements",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I test a combination of conditions before executing a specific action?**\n\nStudents have used `if` and `if-else` statements to execute blocks of code based on a condition. In this lesson, students explore the functionality of nested `if` statements and learn to use these to test a combination of conditions. They also learn how to use the `length()` method in the `String` class to find the length of a `String` object. Students consider scenarios where they would need to test multiple conditions and practice evaluating nested `if` statements to determine the output of a code segment. They then plan and implement an algorithm using nested `if` statements to test a combination of conditions.",
        "preparation": "* Print copies of the Writing Algorithms handout (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can I test a combination of conditions before executing a specific action?**\n\nYou have used `if` and `if-else` statements to execute blocks of code based on a condition. In this lesson, you explore the functionality of nested `if` statements and learn how to use these to test a combination of conditions. You also learn how to use the `length()` method in the `String` class to find the length of a `String` object. You consider scenarios where you would need to test multiple conditions and practice evaluating nested `if` statements to determine the output of a code segment. You then plan and implement an algorithm using nested `if` statements to test a combination of conditions."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Nested If Statements",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Logical Operators",
      "name": "Lesson 6: Logical Operators",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can logical operators be used to evaluate multiple conditions?**\n\nStudents have previously learned to use the NOT ( `!` ) operator to reverse the outcome of a Boolean expression. In this lesson, they explore the use of the AND ( `&&` ) and OR ( `||` ) operators and how these can be used instead of nested `if` statements to test multiple conditions. Students learn about short-circuit evaluation and practice using truth tables to evaluate a Boolean expression involving logical operators.",
        "preparation": "* Print copies of the Truth Tables handout (one for each student)\n",
        "student_overview": "**How can logical operators be used to evaluate multiple conditions?**\n\nYou have previously learned to use the NOT ( `!` ) operator to reverse the outcome of a Boolean expression. In this lesson, you explore the use of the AND ( `&&` ) and OR ( `||` ) operators and how these can be used instead of nested `if` statements to test multiple conditions. You learn about short-circuited evaluation and practice using truth tables to evaluate a Boolean expression involving logical operators."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Logical Operators",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "De Morgan's Laws",
      "name": "Lesson 7: De Morgan's Laws",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What are De Morgan's Laws?**\n\nIn this lesson, students learn about De Morgan's Laws and how they are applied to Boolean expressions. They explore how equivalent Boolean expressions evaluate to the same value in all cases. Students then use truth tables to evaluate compound Boolean expressions and prove De Morgan's Laws.",
        "preparation": "* Print copies of the De Morgan's Laws handout (one for each student)\n* Print the De Morgan's Laws Stations resource\n* Create stations around the classroom as indicated on the De Morgan's Laws Stations resource",
        "student_overview": "**What are De Morgan's Laws?**\n\nYou have learned to use logical operators to create compound Boolean expressions. In this lesson, you learn about De Morgan's Laws and how they are applied to Boolean expressions. You explore how equivalent Boolean expressions evaluate to the same value in all cases. You then use truth tables to evaluate compound Boolean expressions and prove De Morgan's Laws."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "De Morgan's Laws",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Multi-Selection Statements",
      "name": "Lesson 8: Multi-Selection Statements",
      "absolute_position": 8,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I specify different outcomes for different conditions?**\n\nIn this lesson, students expand their knowledge of selection statements to evaluate and implement multi-selection statements. They explore the functionality of multi-selection statements and learn to use these to test a combination of conditions. Students then practice writing algorithms using multi-selection statements to solve problems.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Multi-Selection Statements* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can I specify different outcomes for different conditions?**\n\nIn this lesson, you expand your knowledge of selection statements to evaluate and implement multi-selection statements. You explore the functionality of multi-selection statements and learn to use these to test a combination of conditions. You then practice writing algorithms using multi-selection statements to solve problems."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Multi-Selection Statements",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "For Loops",
      "name": "Lesson 9: For Loops",
      "absolute_position": 9,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I write more efficient and readable code using `for` loops to repeat actions a set number of times?**\n\nStudents learn about the structure and functionality of a `for` loop and explore how it can be used to repeat a task a specific number of times. They identify similarities and differences between `while` loops and `for` loops and practice tracing code segments involving a `for` loop to determine the output. Students then practice converting `while` loops to `for` loops and using `for` loops to repeat a task a specific number of times and identify ideal scenarios for using each type of loop.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *For Loops* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can I write more efficient and readable code using `for` loops to repeat actions a set number of times?**\n\nYou learn about the structure and functionality of a `for` loop and explore how it can be used to repeat an action a specific number of times. You identify similarities and differences between `while` loops and `for` loops and practice tracing code segments involving a `for` loop to determine the output. You then practice converting `while` loops to `for` loops and using `for` loops to repeat a task a specific number of times and identify ideal scenarios for using each type of loop."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "For Loops",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Implementing String Algorithms",
      "name": "Lesson 10: Implementing String Algorithms",
      "absolute_position": 10,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What methods can I use to write algorithms for parsing String objects?**\n\nIn this lesson, students are exposed to the `String` class and learn how to implement standard `String` algorithms using the `substring()` method. Students first investigate reversing a `String` object in order to determine if a sentence is a palindrome. Then, students practice using the `substring()` method and conditional expressions to determine if a `String` object meets a certain criteria. Finally, they practice creating algorithms to count how many `String` objects meet a certain criteria.\n",
        "student_overview": "**How can I implement algorithms for parsing String objects?**\n\nIn this lesson, you will be introduced to the `String` class and learn how to implement standard `String` algorithms using the `substring()` method. You will start by exploring how to reverse a `String` object to determine if a sentence is a palindrome. Next, you will practice using the `substring()` method along with conditional expressions to evaluate whether a `String` object meets a specific criteria. Finally, you will develop algorithms to count the occurrences of `String` objects that meet certain criteria.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Implementing String Algorithms",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Nested Iteration",
      "name": "Lesson 11: Nested Iteration",
      "absolute_position": 11,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I adjust loop control variables of nested loops to produce different output?**\n\nStudents have already been exposed to loops, and will now discover nested iteration through nested `for` loops. Students explore a hands-on activity to recognize similarities between nested `for` loops and the movement of hands on a clock. Students then investigate different ways nested iteration can be used to produce printed patterns and then practice tracing nested loops. Finally, they automate repetitive programming tasks by writing their own nested `for` loops. ",
        "preparation": "* Choose to use the clock face cutouts or the online version\n* Preview the *Nested Iteration* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can I adjust loop control variables of nested loops to produce different output?**\n\nYou have already seen and used `for` loops. Now, you will discover nested iteration through nested `for` loops. You explore a hands-on activity wherein you will recognize similarities between nested `for` loops and the movement of hands on a clock. You’ll then investigate different ways nested iteration can be used to produce printed patterns and then practice tracing nested loops. Finally, you will automate repetitive programming tasks by writing your own nested `for` loops. \n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Nested Iteration",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-12",
      "name": "Lesson 12: Informal Run-Time Analysis",
      "absolute_position": 12,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I determine the number of times a specific statement is executed within a loop in a program?**\n\nThis lesson helps students build foundational skills in informal run-time analysis by focusing on how often each statement in a program executes. Students begin by tracing code to determine execution counts, then apply these skills in hands-on partner activities using iterative and nested loops.",
        "preparation": "* Print copies of the Informal Run-Time Analysis activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can I determine the number of times a specific statement is executed within a loop in a program?**\n\nHave you ever wondered how many times a line of code actually runs in a program? Today you learn how to figure that out. You practice tracing code to count how many times each statement runs, especially in loops. You also learn tips and patterns to help you estimate how a program behaves without running it."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-12",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Creative Coding with the Console Project",
      "name": "Project 1a: Creative Coding with the Console Project",
      "absolute_position": 13,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "assessment": true,
        "overview": "**How is my growth as a software engineer reflected in my project?**\n\nStudents continue to develop their Creative Coding with the Console Project to create a program that portrays a personal interest or solves a problem using the console. Students first self-assess their work to evaluate their progress in completing project requirements, then continue development of your program. They conduct acceptance testing to determine which of their user stories are complete and use the self-assessment and peer feedback to prioritize their remaining tasks. Students use this feedback to finalize development before sharing their projects with their peers to celebrate their successes.",
        "student_overview": "**How is my growth as a software engineer reflected in my project?**\n\nYou continue to develop your Creative Coding with the Console Project to create a program that portrays a personal interest or solves a problem using the console. You first self-assess your work to evaluate your progress in completing project requirements, then continue development of your program. You conduct acceptance testing to determine which of your user stories are complete and use the self-assessment and peer feedback to prioritize your remaining tasks. You use this feedback to finalize development before sharing your project with your peers to celebrate your success."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Creative Coding with the Console Project",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa2-alt-2025"
      }
    },
