  ],
  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "1cdf2c52-d307-427b-979f-6dd33bd406cd",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned how to give instructions to our `Painter` objects by calling methods from the `Painter` class. When we are trying to get our `Painter` objects to navigate and paint in The Neighborhood, we have to be specific about the order we want the instructions to be executed. The order we give our instructions is one of the components of an algorithm.",
        "name": "Components of an Algorithm",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1cdf2c52-d307-427b-979f-6dd33bd406cd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96d311d3-649d-4fdc-82e6-48aed51e2eaa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "30c767ad-f9f5-4212-8d52-7bbf9344a815",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you know or remember about algorithms?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall what they learned about algorithms in Computer Science Principles (CSP), including the components of an algorithm such as sequencing, selection, and iteration. Students identify sequencing as the order that steps are executed and make connections to how they have been using sequencing in The Neighborhood. Students may recall that selection is used to determine a different set of instructions to execute based on a condition and that iteration is used to execute a set of instructions a specific number of times or while a condition is true.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "30c767ad-f9f5-4212-8d52-7bbf9344a815",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96d311d3-649d-4fdc-82e6-48aed51e2eaa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a929e03e-b60f-4ed2-8454-452b4ded6b69",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***algorithm*** and introduce the components of an algorithm."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a929e03e-b60f-4ed2-8454-452b4ded6b69",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96d311d3-649d-4fdc-82e6-48aed51e2eaa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66e2af8c-e0f6-4994-883a-b5440cf399f2",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66e2af8c-e0f6-4994-883a-b5440cf399f2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d40d393f-e5c6-4475-90d9-07ccdd5917c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6414e1f6-66ee-45bd-8b4f-4bb8499239b2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned how to call methods to have our `Painter` objects perform specific tasks in a certain order to achieve a goal. You likely noticed that when we were doing this, we were often repeating the same set of instructions, such as when we wanted to move and paint several times in a row. Let's find out how we can expand our algorithms to use sequencing and iteration so we don't have to write the same lines of code over and over again.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6414e1f6-66ee-45bd-8b4f-4bb8499239b2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d40d393f-e5c6-4475-90d9-07ccdd5917c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2ce2fb55-6dec-4959-a05f-26e73f8025c0",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Loops and Boolean Methods"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2ce2fb55-6dec-4959-a05f-26e73f8025c0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d40d393f-e5c6-4475-90d9-07ccdd5917c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2cc4d596-c298-46f2-9fd3-cee56638cde0",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify the `canMove()`, `isOnBucket()`, and `hasPaint()` methods used in the program and share ideas about what each method does. Students should also notice that these methods are used with `while` loops to determine if the `Painter` object can move or has paint and repeats the instructions as long as the condition is `true`. Students might wonder about the similarities and differences between these methods and those they have used previously or if there are other methods they can use to check other conditions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce `boolean` values and the `Painter` class methods.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some scenarios that you can think of where you would want to know if something is either true or false? Why might you need to know that?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share examples from their personal lives and experiences, such as deciding if they needed a jacket based on the weather or if they could hang out with their friends based on whether they had finished their homework or chores.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2cc4d596-c298-46f2-9fd3-cee56638cde0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d40d393f-e5c6-4475-90d9-07ccdd5917c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9b41731e-3286-406e-b88a-4710fc8eff4d",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "These new methods in the `Painter` class give us useful information about whether a `Painter` object can move or has paint. Unlike the other methods we have used so far, like `move()` and `paint()`, these methods give us either a `true` or `false` value when we call them that we can use to decide whether to repeat a set of instructions. Let's take a closer look at how we can do this.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Loops and Boolean Methods",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9b41731e-3286-406e-b88a-4710fc8eff4d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d40d393f-e5c6-4475-90d9-07ccdd5917c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3d336ab9-9da6-484b-97f0-69669168fea8",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *While Loops*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3d336ab9-9da6-484b-97f0-69669168fea8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d40d393f-e5c6-4475-90d9-07ccdd5917c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a603e15-f550-4103-85c8-8e8cab9cc16a",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the example flowchart of washing dishes.\n\n**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2 through 5. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Loops and Boolean Methods"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a603e15-f550-4103-85c8-8e8cab9cc16a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d40d393f-e5c6-4475-90d9-07ccdd5917c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9da97669-24c1-4e24-95fe-3591816c0752",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to share what happens when a condition is never `true`."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9da97669-24c1-4e24-95fe-3591816c0752",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d40d393f-e5c6-4475-90d9-07ccdd5917c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d3fcb9d4-91bb-4f06-a2ae-35122d094124",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the syntax and functionality of a `while` loop and define ***iteration statement*** and ***condition***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that iteration is required when we need to repeat an action until a condition is met, but we don't know in advance how many times it must run.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate that if the condition evaluates to `false` initially, the loop body is not executed at all."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d3fcb9d4-91bb-4f06-a2ae-35122d094124",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d40d393f-e5c6-4475-90d9-07ccdd5917c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f32e4f7b-6600-4122-9ac8-729360ace0f2",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We now know how to implement two components of algorithms in Java – sequencing and iteration. Software engineers often plan their algorithms in natural language first before writing code. This is an important step that helps us better understand a problem and plan the steps we need to take to develop a solution.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Writing Algorithms",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f32e4f7b-6600-4122-9ac8-729360ace0f2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d40d393f-e5c6-4475-90d9-07ccdd5917c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "95928594-c46b-4b78-b1cb-e2e239248f5b",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Writing Algorithms handout.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This and future \"Writing Algorithms\" activity guides provide guiding prompts and space for students to decompose problems and plan their solutions. Students do not need to complete all sections! However, if students get stuck, these are helpful for thinking through the problem to get unstuck."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "95928594-c46b-4b78-b1cb-e2e239248f5b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d40d393f-e5c6-4475-90d9-07ccdd5917c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dd262c3b-cf99-4220-80df-0008b0fbf7c3",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs or small groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to choose one of the problems and use the problem solving process to plan their solution.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 6 on Code Studio to complete Levels 6 and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 6, then continue to complete Level 7 to implement their solution for their chosen problem.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Using Loops and Boolean Methods",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice levels can be used as formative assessments to gauge understanding of vocabulary presented in the lesson and writing algorithms using sequencing and iteration."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dd262c3b-cf99-4220-80df-0008b0fbf7c3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d40d393f-e5c6-4475-90d9-07ccdd5917c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b8a23052-ef95-4076-abf2-1954acc45ad0",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software engineers write algorithms every day to solve problems, many of which consist of the same components you just implemented today in your own algorithms. We have expanded our programming skills and knowledge quite a bit today!",
        "name": "Three W's",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b8a23052-ef95-4076-abf2-1954acc45ad0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1106bb8b-00b5-4a47-8a7f-61ff19d59fdf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b4dc8d3c-3ca0-4736-9812-7ac7dccf6216",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did we learn today?*\n* *So what?*\n* *Now what?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students highlight the concepts and vocabulary they learned in this lesson, such as `boolean` and iteration. Students also identify the syntax for writing a `while` loop and how it can be used to repeat a set of instructions in The Neighborhood. They should realize that they now have the knowledge to develop more complex algorithms with two of the three components of an algorithm and might suggest selection as the next component to learn.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b4dc8d3c-3ca0-4736-9812-7ac7dccf6216",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1106bb8b-00b5-4a47-8a7f-61ff19d59fdf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "06367e38-df8e-4dfa-b04b-74ad80b5157f",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "06367e38-df8e-4dfa-b04b-74ad80b5157f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1106bb8b-00b5-4a47-8a7f-61ff19d59fdf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6e34acd6-61b0-46ca-8bf1-a362756eee6f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6e34acd6-61b0-46ca-8bf1-a362756eee6f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1106bb8b-00b5-4a47-8a7f-61ff19d59fdf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "67c10043-a14a-4fa9-834b-5c6ff7252aac",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We previously learned that an algorithm can be constructed using sequencing, selection, and iteration. So far, we have learned how to implement sequencing and iteration in Java.",
        "name": "Components of an Algorithm",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "67c10043-a14a-4fa9-834b-5c6ff7252aac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d2fee4a1-082d-4781-a6bf-2fb5d7b9305e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "440e5c40-51cd-4400-97dd-ef99a88cbefc",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How do you think we would implement selection in Java?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall selection statements they implemented in Computer Science Discoveries (CSD), Computer Science Principles (CSP), or other similar course and suggest using the `if` instead of `while` to check a condition.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to recall how they implemented selection in previous computer science courses and make suggestions about how this might be achieved in Java based on what they already know. Ask students to consider what keyword they might use in place of `while` to check if a condition is `true` instead of repeating a block of code while a condition is `true`.\n\nUse the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas on the Unit 1 Guide first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "440e5c40-51cd-4400-97dd-ef99a88cbefc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d2fee4a1-082d-4781-a6bf-2fb5d7b9305e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e45012c3-a66c-4e9e-8622-4b0bac5e3bcc",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e45012c3-a66c-4e9e-8622-4b0bac5e3bcc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4b75b330-04fc-4c24-a7c1-b6ae334f3c64",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have used iteration to repeat a block of code while a condition is `true`. We can also use selection to execute a specific block of code if a condition is `true`. Let's take a look at how this works in Java.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4b75b330-04fc-4c24-a7c1-b6ae334f3c64",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "39241120-05de-402c-9cbc-6fcb236dc170",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Selection Statements"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "39241120-05de-402c-9cbc-6fcb236dc170",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6f83e4b2-2b5f-420d-8df0-188a829ba8c4",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the code uses an `if` statement to check if a condition is `true` and only executes the block of code once if the condition is `true`. Students may wonder how they might use an `if` statement with sequencing and iteration to write algorithms in The Neighborhood."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6f83e4b2-2b5f-420d-8df0-188a829ba8c4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0e247626-bd4b-4f02-84b8-e71c9d1260cd",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Conditional Statements*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0e247626-bd4b-4f02-84b8-e71c9d1260cd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c5eb267b-f610-455b-b94a-971061c07623",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain the syntax and functionality of an `if` statement:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***selection statement***\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The condition of an `if` statement"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c5eb267b-f610-455b-b94a-971061c07623",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "620f22e3-fce1-4aef-8231-25e6ebaec0b9",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "With sequencing, selection, and iteration, we can write algorithms that allow our `Painter` objects to make decisions while navigating and painting in The Neighborhood. We can combine these components of an algorithm with methods in the `Painter` class to not only check if a `Painter` object can move in the direction it is facing or is on a paint bucket but also to check if a `Painter` object can move in a different direction or is facing a specific direction.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Selection Statements",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "620f22e3-fce1-4aef-8231-25e6ebaec0b9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8db6011c-5e38-43ec-a333-bb86045b1d8a",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Investigate: Selection Statements handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to investigate the program and complete the Investigate: Selection Statements handout.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Selection Statements"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8db6011c-5e38-43ec-a333-bb86045b1d8a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "431343e2-4d34-4f9f-841e-d00818b84d32",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code and their responses on the Investigate: Selection Statements handout.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to share similarities and differences they notice between selection statements and `while` loops. Ask students how many times the condition is checked in a selection statement in comparison to a `while` loop and suggest scenarios where they would want to use one structure over another."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "431343e2-4d34-4f9f-841e-d00818b84d32",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "73df8aae-536b-409e-a67a-d77ba9bdd137",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have now seen some new methods in the `Painter` class that allow us to check if a `Painter` object can move in a specific direction, if it is currently standing on paint, or if it is currently facing a specific direction. With these, we can allow our `Painter` objects to make decisions about things like which direction to move or whether or not to turn or paint.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "73df8aae-536b-409e-a67a-d77ba9bdd137",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9aeaf646-cea6-4f5d-bd88-9475b79d39a1",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How might these methods be useful to solve problems in The Neighborhood?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest algorithms they have written or problems they have solved before that they could expand using these methods, such as moving along a wall and turning right when a `Painter` object can move south.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students consider problems they have solved before where these methods might have been useful to expand their algorithms. Ask students how they could have simplified their code using these methods with selection and iteration so a `Painter` object could make decisions about which direction to move or turn."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9aeaf646-cea6-4f5d-bd88-9475b79d39a1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ebfdb46d-73eb-4dbe-83bc-b2621945bbfd",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Our `PainterPlus` class has some additional methods that let us do things that the `Painter` class didn't provide. We know our `PainterPlus` class works as intended, so we can extend the `PainterPlus` class to create more specialized versions of `PainterPlus`. A subclass of the `PainterPlus` class would be able to do everything `Painter` and `PainterPlus` objects can do and more! Let's use our knowledge of inheritance and algorithms to solve some problems in The Neighborhood.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Writing Algorithms",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ebfdb46d-73eb-4dbe-83bc-b2621945bbfd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c488fb58-b7a1-4d5b-8400-61004b486def",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Writing Algorithms handout.\n\n**Group:** Place students in pairs or small groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to choose one of the problems and use the problem-solving process to plan their solution.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 3 on Code Studio to complete Levels 3 and 4. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 3, then continue to Level 4 to create a subclass of the `PainterPlus` class and implement their algorithm for their chosen problem.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Writing Algorithms",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice levels can be used as formative assessments to gauge understanding of planning and implementing algorithms using sequencing, selection, and iteration."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c488fb58-b7a1-4d5b-8400-61004b486def",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "34a39a25-db54-405f-b032-f636020e2bd5",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is a good time to commit our code and save our new version of our `PainterPlus` class to the Backpack. Anytime we make changes to our programs, it is helpful to commit our work in case we need to go back to a previous version.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "34a39a25-db54-405f-b032-f636020e2bd5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "da461a37-5ff4-4f0a-af89-ca0f7bf7c1a5",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue committing their code and saving their new `PainterPlus` subclass to the Backpack.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity.\n\nClick the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "da461a37-5ff4-4f0a-af89-ca0f7bf7c1a5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "381d7116-f23d-453c-8e75-2c4569d1b490"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cb495f5f-8244-4f70-95e8-134da446802b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "With inheritance and algorithms, we can develop solutions for a variety of problems in The Neighborhood. Let's take a moment to review what we have learned so far.",
        "name": "Question Stems",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cb495f5f-8244-4f70-95e8-134da446802b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2db6386e-2089-467a-b8ab-bfb0b7cd24fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e81cfd3a-b07c-4632-9529-aa0909274e8f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student an index card or piece of scrap paper.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to write a question on their index card using one of the question stems. Have students turn to a neighbor and take turns asking and answering their questions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e81cfd3a-b07c-4632-9529-aa0909274e8f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2db6386e-2089-467a-b8ab-bfb0b7cd24fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "95b8f480-7901-491e-bb0f-66bd992343c1",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "95b8f480-7901-491e-bb0f-66bd992343c1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2db6386e-2089-467a-b8ab-bfb0b7cd24fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "38887ebe-849a-4d7f-8ddf-486aac651505",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "38887ebe-849a-4d7f-8ddf-486aac651505",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2db6386e-2089-467a-b8ab-bfb0b7cd24fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "827375ff-49dc-4d20-80ee-bf7ce2ac6e0e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Imagine you're organizing a field trip for your class. You check the weather and see it’s supposed to rain tomorrow. What would your plan be if it rains? What about if it doesn't?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that in real life, we often prepare for both possibilities when something is true and when it's false. This sets up the idea that `if/else` lets us write two different code paths based on whether a condition is true or not. It also helps introduce the idea of negation (e.g., `if NOT sunny`)."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "827375ff-49dc-4d20-80ee-bf7ce2ac6e0e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3016b81-49f5-4978-b3a5-8c470291739e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5ece5f62-49c9-4515-9773-cd2f50d9c2aa",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5ece5f62-49c9-4515-9773-cd2f50d9c2aa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56ca48ea-c14a-4358-9390-c80b62d645c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "950dfe09-a3a8-40a3-a1c3-2019278b9b15",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned to use `if` statements to execute a block of code if a condition is `true` and `while` loops to repeat a block of code as long as a condition is `true`. What if we wanted to execute a specific block of code if a condition is NOT `true`?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "950dfe09-a3a8-40a3-a1c3-2019278b9b15",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56ca48ea-c14a-4358-9390-c80b62d645c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4c9908bc-cfb6-4bbf-b538-37e4df6621c7",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Selection and Logic"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4c9908bc-cfb6-4bbf-b538-37e4df6621c7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56ca48ea-c14a-4358-9390-c80b62d645c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c0b18173-65b1-49a7-9044-83449dc97420",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice the `!` (NOT) before the condition for the `if` statement and the `if/else` statement that executes a separate block of code if the condition is false. Students may wonder when they would choose to use the NOT ( `!` ) operator instead of an `if/else` statement.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***logical operator***.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Focus only on the NOT operator in this lesson. Students learn about the AND and OR operators in a future lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c0b18173-65b1-49a7-9044-83449dc97420",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56ca48ea-c14a-4358-9390-c80b62d645c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b75ee4f3-e824-430e-a9b3-d61b5acb79ce",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Investigate: Selection and Logic handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to investigate the program and complete the Investigate: Selection and Logic handout.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Selection and Logic",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Selection and Logic"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b75ee4f3-e824-430e-a9b3-d61b5acb79ce",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56ca48ea-c14a-4358-9390-c80b62d645c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f7fb9568-3307-4003-923b-13fb748a1f7d",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code and their responses on the Investigate: Selection and Logic handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***two-way selection statement***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Two-Way Selection and NOT*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f7fb9568-3307-4003-923b-13fb748a1f7d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56ca48ea-c14a-4358-9390-c80b62d645c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4251f509-ed6d-46d7-a87d-eba2962a615b",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How can two-way selection statements and the NOT ( `!` ) operator be useful in the algorithms we have developed so far?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest using two-way selection statements to execute a block of code if the condition is `true` and a separate block of code if the condition is `false`. Students may also suggest using the NOT ( `!` ) operator to execute a block of code if a condition is not `true`, such as turning if a `Painter` object cannot move forward in the direction it is facing.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas on the Unit 1 Guide first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4251f509-ed6d-46d7-a87d-eba2962a615b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56ca48ea-c14a-4358-9390-c80b62d645c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "02f5cf25-ed0a-4975-abfb-2240baf887c3",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "As you work through these problems, use the problem solving process and decomposition strategies to break them down into manageable tasks. Write your algorithms in pseudocode so you can easily implement and refine them in Java.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Writing Algorithms",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "02f5cf25-ed0a-4975-abfb-2240baf887c3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56ca48ea-c14a-4358-9390-c80b62d645c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0da454f6-808e-4d2c-84b4-45c95112cb13",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 3 on Code Studio to complete Levels 3 and 4. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 3, then continue to complete a choice level on Level 4 to create a subclass of the `PainterPlus` class and implement their algorithm using two-way selection statements and the NOT ( `!` ) operator.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Writing Algorithms",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice levels can be used as formative assessments to gauge understanding of planning and using two-way selection statements, the problem solving process, and pseudocode to plan and implement algorithms."
          },
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Remind students to use the problem solving process to plan their solution and write pseudocode for their algorithms. Emphasize the use of natural language when writing pseudocode. Allow students to write their pseudocode in whichever language they are most comfortable to support the focus on planning their algorithms rather than focusing on specific structures or languages."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0da454f6-808e-4d2c-84b4-45c95112cb13",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56ca48ea-c14a-4358-9390-c80b62d645c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3df7338c-b037-4710-937c-3be8b16fe65e",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is a good time to commit our code and save our new `PainterPlus` subclass to the Backpack. Anytime we make changes to our programs, it is helpful to commit our work in case we need to go back to a previous version.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3df7338c-b037-4710-937c-3be8b16fe65e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56ca48ea-c14a-4358-9390-c80b62d645c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "af8d64a2-b553-4897-ad43-cdef4f103eaa",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue committing their code and saving their new `PainterPlus` subclass to the Backpack.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity.\n\nClick the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "af8d64a2-b553-4897-ad43-cdef4f103eaa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "56ca48ea-c14a-4358-9390-c80b62d645c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a3235c95-f834-4acb-a5ec-8bf5ef1dcf04",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a3235c95-f834-4acb-a5ec-8bf5ef1dcf04",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ee430c5-8e96-43e1-bc35-56649d31b065"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e604cb41-8d65-409f-851d-7b228ac4df81",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e604cb41-8d65-409f-851d-7b228ac4df81",
