      }
    },
    {
      "key": "335902a6-1cc2-4919-a5e0-58f66f7b43fc",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "335902a6-1cc2-4919-a5e0-58f66f7b43fc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ee430c5-8e96-43e1-bc35-56649d31b065"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "43ec06ae-d906-4c9b-9eda-e8fb2b02a3ba",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we compare two primitive values to check for equality, we use the equality operator to check if both values are the same. It's easy to tell if two numbers or `boolean` values are the same, such as three equals three or `false` does not equal `true`. However, it's not quite as easy when comparing two objects for equality.",
        "name": "Object Equality",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "43ec06ae-d906-4c9b-9eda-e8fb2b02a3ba",
        "lesson_activity.key": "17228609-2438-40b1-997c-6125d7ed62e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "abbe9241-2d1b-47c4-8733-911c223daccf",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What does it mean to you for two objects to be considered equal?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest that two objects are considered equal if they have the same values for their attributes.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "abbe9241-2d1b-47c4-8733-911c223daccf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "17228609-2438-40b1-997c-6125d7ed62e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "35ce8ebd-dfd8-4f35-b3e6-240b0977ff93",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Do we consider these two objects to be equal? Why or why not?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share whether they consider the example objects equivalent and provide their reasoning. For example, students may suggest that they are equivalent because they share the same values for their attributes or that they are not equivalent because they are two separate objects.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How about different names for the same object? Do we consider these to be equal? Why or why not?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students might have varying opinions on whether they consider different names for the same object as equivalent. Have students share their opinions and provide their reasoning. For example, students may suggest that they are equivalent because they both refer to one object or are not equivalent because they are two different references.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Share additional examples and ask students how they decide these are equivalent. For example,\n* *If we had two basketballs, would they be considered equal? Why or why not?*\n* *If we had a song on a playlist twice, would they be considered equal? Why or why not?*\n* *Do any of you have a nickname? Are your nickname and your full first name the same object?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "35ce8ebd-dfd8-4f35-b3e6-240b0977ff93",
        "lesson_activity.key": "17228609-2438-40b1-997c-6125d7ed62e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f8e11dcf-1793-4aeb-9c5c-106f95e9ca85",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f8e11dcf-1793-4aeb-9c5c-106f95e9ca85",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ef4ea0b8-db68-485e-be53-888c9b70056c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0a4dce5f-3abe-4927-99e9-a62787215376",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "A reference variable stores a pointer to an object in memory and does not store the object itself. Because of this, comparing reference variables for equality does not always give us the results we might expect.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0a4dce5f-3abe-4927-99e9-a62787215376",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ef4ea0b8-db68-485e-be53-888c9b70056c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "36e822a6-fcf9-4be2-9d56-4ebff3b08490",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Comparing Objects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "36e822a6-fcf9-4be2-9d56-4ebff3b08490",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ef4ea0b8-db68-485e-be53-888c9b70056c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "963775f8-2f6b-46e0-bf26-71460b230ed9",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that some object comparisons returned `true` while others returned `false`. Students realize that the reference variables assigned to another reference variable return `true`, but the reference variables pointing to new objects return `false`. Students may wonder why these comparisons return `false` when the values for the instance variables are the same and how they might check these values for equality."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "963775f8-2f6b-46e0-bf26-71460b230ed9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ef4ea0b8-db68-485e-be53-888c9b70056c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "365dfc50-f96b-4dd7-80cb-d4da4693e485",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Aliases",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Comparing Objects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "365dfc50-f96b-4dd7-80cb-d4da4693e485",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ef4ea0b8-db68-485e-be53-888c9b70056c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9146e3a9-261e-465c-b1fb-6c090e01e20e",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9146e3a9-261e-465c-b1fb-6c090e01e20e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ef4ea0b8-db68-485e-be53-888c9b70056c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "51a39e98-6d79-4925-acf2-99e3d9adfa59",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When reference variables point to the same object, they are known as aliases. These reference variables point to the same location in memory and not separate objects.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "51a39e98-6d79-4925-acf2-99e3d9adfa59",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ef4ea0b8-db68-485e-be53-888c9b70056c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e95025ce-5e00-40c0-9d1c-da4bc14354bf",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Aliasing*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e95025ce-5e00-40c0-9d1c-da4bc14354bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ef4ea0b8-db68-485e-be53-888c9b70056c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d52c6afe-f727-4ebb-a978-4706b67f8a6a",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***alias*** and demonstrate the example.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When would it be useful to use the `==` or `!=` operators with objects? When would these NOT be useful?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest using the equality operators to check if two reference variables are aliases or if an object is `null`. Students note that the equality operators are not useful when checking if two objects have the same values for the instance variables."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d52c6afe-f727-4ebb-a978-4706b67f8a6a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ef4ea0b8-db68-485e-be53-888c9b70056c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "35d3ddeb-5f80-4840-859c-17001cb57899",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We previously learned that the `Object` class is the superclass of all classes in Java. It has methods that we can override to be more specific to our programs.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "The equals() Method",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "35d3ddeb-5f80-4840-859c-17001cb57899",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ef4ea0b8-db68-485e-be53-888c9b70056c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fb03fc05-c994-4930-a56b-58a02ec5f95b",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to review the `Object` class and the `toString()` method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *The equals() Method*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the `equals()` method in the `Object` class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall overriding and introduce the method signature for the `equals()` method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *The parameter in the `equals()` method is of type `Object`, which means the parameter in the `equals()` methods we write must be of type `Object`. How can we treat the parameter as the type we need so we can access its instance variables?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall using casting to treat a value as a different type and suggest using casting to treat the parameter as the type needed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fb03fc05-c994-4930-a56b-58a02ec5f95b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ef4ea0b8-db68-485e-be53-888c9b70056c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03658472-a115-4bc2-b511-7f3cd6b7ca31",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain how to override the `equals()` method:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The method signature must be the same as the `equals()` method in the `Object` class\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Cast the `Object` parameter as the type we need\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Checking if the `Object` parameter point to the same object as `this` object\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Using the `instanceof` operator to check if the `Object` parameter is an instance of the class\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5 and 6. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to Level 6 to complete a choice level to debug the program.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: The equals() Method",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of overriding the `equals()` method.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of overriding the `equals()` method."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03658472-a115-4bc2-b511-7f3cd6b7ca31",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ef4ea0b8-db68-485e-be53-888c9b70056c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ad24eb7c-d5ed-4cc5-90dd-58f7748e2cff",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Comparing objects for equality can be tricky, but overriding the `equals()` method in our classes makes it easier for us to check if two objects have the same values assigned to their instance variables. Let's see if we can capture what we have learned today in one sentence!",
        "name": "But, Because, So",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ad24eb7c-d5ed-4cc5-90dd-58f7748e2cff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a0ab4037-a452-45ce-9595-e0689803c6ef"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d1855c17-4a46-41ce-be74-8e818590f073",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a sticky note or scrap piece of paper.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the prompt on the sticky note or scrap piece of paper.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, have students share their responses with a neighbor."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d1855c17-4a46-41ce-be74-8e818590f073",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a0ab4037-a452-45ce-9595-e0689803c6ef"
      }
    },
