    {
      "key": "d68a7544-30bb-4927-b476-0a113f2d48c3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Patterns in the data can help us decide how we want to communicate its story visually. How we choose to illustrate these patterns can emphasize the point we want to make.",
        "name": "Finding Patterns",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d68a7544-30bb-4927-b476-0a113f2d48c3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "df3a0885-b797-4683-bac5-d6245ad8805b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46363cef-47eb-45ad-b187-ca273d92693c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What patterns or relationships do you see in this dataset?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share patterns and relationships they notice in the dataset.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students share patterns and relationships they notice with a partner first, then discuss as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46363cef-47eb-45ad-b187-ca273d92693c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "df3a0885-b797-4683-bac5-d6245ad8805b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "da3220e7-2260-4b05-974e-04c0b4ea29b6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "da3220e7-2260-4b05-974e-04c0b4ea29b6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "be7bc8d4-bd39-4778-a27c-0f8647f31295"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "be25a577-39a6-4cfe-81d0-b16e622068ee",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have used `if` statements to check a condition and execute a block of code if that condition is `true`. Sometimes there are multiple conditions that need to be true before a block of code is executed. Today, we'll explore how we can use nested `if` statements to test multiple conditions.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "be25a577-39a6-4cfe-81d0-b16e622068ee",
        "lesson_activity.key": "be7bc8d4-bd39-4778-a27c-0f8647f31295"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7aa25db2-4693-4a31-91ee-f609914366ef",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Nested if Statements"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7aa25db2-4693-4a31-91ee-f609914366ef",
        "lesson_activity.key": "be7bc8d4-bd39-4778-a27c-0f8647f31295"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c7dec69f-88fd-48f6-8bdd-084bc6fe9979",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice the nested `if` statements and that both the outer and inner `if` statements have to be `true` for the code to execute. Students may wonder if they can also nest `if` statements inside the `else` statement or if there are other ways to check multiple conditions."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c7dec69f-88fd-48f6-8bdd-084bc6fe9979",
        "lesson_activity.key": "be7bc8d4-bd39-4778-a27c-0f8647f31295"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "69f816bc-c210-42f6-8a4e-1cc168b139ac",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2 and 3. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Nested If Statements",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Nested if Statements"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "69f816bc-c210-42f6-8a4e-1cc168b139ac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "be7bc8d4-bd39-4778-a27c-0f8647f31295"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b7c404eb-e4a0-4d87-ba7f-a0cd263ed6b0",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***nested conditional statement*** and introduce the example code segment.\n\n**Do This:** Click through the animated slides to demonstrate the flowchart for the code segment:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Explain each branch of the flowchart\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> First condition is `true`\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Second condition is `true`\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `\"Both true!\"` is printed "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b7c404eb-e4a0-4d87-ba7f-a0cd263ed6b0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "be7bc8d4-bd39-4778-a27c-0f8647f31295"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9eb4232d-231d-4636-adca-caff460b431e",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "What if we wanted to find words in a list that met certain criteria, like words with a certain number of characters? Since a `String` is an object, the `String` class has a method to help us solve this problem!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9eb4232d-231d-4636-adca-caff460b431e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "be7bc8d4-bd39-4778-a27c-0f8647f31295"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "286b321b-81cb-4652-b366-05734bb836c4",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that each character in a `String` is at an index which starts at `0`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the cause of an `IndexOutOfBoundsException`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate the `length()` method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the self-check question to determine the length of the first `String`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the self-check question to determine the length of the second `String`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why does the `length()` method not return the last index in a `String`?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall that the last index of a `String` object is one less than its size, so the value for `length()` is one more than the last index."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "286b321b-81cb-4652-b366-05734bb836c4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "be7bc8d4-bd39-4778-a27c-0f8647f31295"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "eb41ba5b-5864-4f18-aa89-1dc7a60cba3a",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We can use nested `if` statements to check if multiple conditions are `true` before executing a block of code. When we are making decisions about how to visualize data, we might choose to display images and shapes based on multiple conditions.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Using Nested If Statements",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "eb41ba5b-5864-4f18-aa89-1dc7a60cba3a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "be7bc8d4-bd39-4778-a27c-0f8647f31295"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "69907000-2acc-4a12-b643-2f628dc9bd8d",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Writing Algorithms handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to work with their partner to write pseudocode for one of the problems.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You can also have students draw a flowchart to illustrate their algorithm in addition to or instead of writing pseudocode."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "69907000-2acc-4a12-b643-2f628dc9bd8d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "be7bc8d4-bd39-4778-a27c-0f8647f31295"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5b95d7de-9cef-405a-8817-5ad6c9501ba6",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 4 on Code Studio to complete Levels 4, 5, and 6. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 4, then continue to Level 5 to implement their algorithm. On Level 6, students use nested `if` statements while traversing a one-dimensional (1D) array.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Nested if Statements",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of evaluating code segments using nested `if` statements.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of writing algorithms using nested `if` statements."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5b95d7de-9cef-405a-8817-5ad6c9501ba6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "be7bc8d4-bd39-4778-a27c-0f8647f31295"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2f3c6913-085f-4bb4-9dde-fe09c8a2285b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Discuss:** *Today we learned how to use nested `if` statements to check multiple conditions before running a block of code. Why might that be more useful than a single `if` statement?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should explain that nested `if` statements allow programs to make more specific decisions by checking an additional condition only if the first condition is true. This helps programs handle complex scenarios where different outcomes depend on combinations of conditions. Students should also be able to give a concrete example from their pseudocode or code implementation.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2f3c6913-085f-4bb4-9dde-fe09c8a2285b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4572920b-0745-4c5e-b09c-bb9850230a8e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "438118a4-d9b7-49ee-8dec-398777d053ac",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "438118a4-d9b7-49ee-8dec-398777d053ac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4572920b-0745-4c5e-b09c-bb9850230a8e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c9e42cf7-6da8-4c97-84a8-521a640b795c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c9e42cf7-6da8-4c97-84a8-521a640b795c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4572920b-0745-4c5e-b09c-bb9850230a8e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c56c68f9-6185-4f13-8349-9ccc01df00d3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have seen how we can represent loops and conditionals as flowcharts. Flowcharts can be used to represent algorithms so we can easily plan and visualize its steps.",
        "name": "Representing Algorithms",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c56c68f9-6185-4f13-8349-9ccc01df00d3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a7dfc9f2-42f7-4a92-bf6f-96db6c19220f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "217edf05-aa18-457d-92be-0ccc81b3cb43",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the scenario.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to draw a flowchart to represent the algorithm needed to solve the problem.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "There is space on the Unit 4 Guide for students to draw their flowcharts.\n\nIt is not important for students to use specific symbols for each step. The goal is for students to practice using flowcharts as a tool to visualize algorithms as an alternative or supplement to writing pseudocode."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "217edf05-aa18-457d-92be-0ccc81b3cb43",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a7dfc9f2-42f7-4a92-bf6f-96db6c19220f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "19a773a1-7ab3-4ee3-ac57-ea0e10fd9a91",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share their flowcharts with a neighbor to compare and modify their flowcharts.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, you can also have students share their flowcharts as a class to identify similarities and differences in other flowcharts. You could also have students identify best practices for creating flowcharts to represent algorithms, such as symbols to use for decisions and tasks."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "19a773a1-7ab3-4ee3-ac57-ea0e10fd9a91",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a7dfc9f2-42f7-4a92-bf6f-96db6c19220f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "56141ff3-9fe2-4749-8fcb-88cd852e3ecf",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "56141ff3-9fe2-4749-8fcb-88cd852e3ecf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "77b11936-13e6-4543-aed9-412cdaca6e21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cd24ae3e-f01c-495b-922e-ecb2670482a3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We previously learned to use the NOT operator to negate a Boolean expression. We have also learned to use nested `if` statements to check multiple conditions before executing a block of code. There are more logical operators that we can use to check multiple conditions in one line.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cd24ae3e-f01c-495b-922e-ecb2670482a3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "77b11936-13e6-4543-aed9-412cdaca6e21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "92a13831-c650-406b-8eab-746f5ced3362",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Logical Operators"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "92a13831-c650-406b-8eab-746f5ced3362",
        "lesson_activity.key": "77b11936-13e6-4543-aed9-412cdaca6e21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c176d7f3-1ebb-43a1-95c7-20f0896f69d2",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice the program uses `&&` operator in the condition and share ideas about its functionality. Students may wonder how this is similar and different from using nested `if` statements."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c176d7f3-1ebb-43a1-95c7-20f0896f69d2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "77b11936-13e6-4543-aed9-412cdaca6e21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9555039e-1a77-4b68-bb4c-64e4d5403518",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Logical Operators",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Logical Operators"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9555039e-1a77-4b68-bb4c-64e4d5403518",
        "lesson_activity.key": "77b11936-13e6-4543-aed9-412cdaca6e21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "49e6df93-1763-4ab1-9e1e-0c35f99a4bb6",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the logical operators.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***compound Boolean expression*** and demonstrate the example.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How might logical operators help us simplify the use of conditional statements?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest using logical operators instead of multiple or nested `if` statements to check whether multiple conditions are `true` or if at least one of two conditions are `true`.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "49e6df93-1763-4ab1-9e1e-0c35f99a4bb6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "77b11936-13e6-4543-aed9-412cdaca6e21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4272ead1-e9e2-466f-ab14-f37dc1c45d6f",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *In the previous lesson, we used nested `if` statements to solve this scenario. How would this solution change using logical operators?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share examples of how they would rewrite the code they wrote in the previous lesson to use logical operators instead of nested `if` statements.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the example conditional statement using a logical operator."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4272ead1-e9e2-466f-ab14-f37dc1c45d6f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "77b11936-13e6-4543-aed9-412cdaca6e21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dab8d54a-d821-4f3d-8b44-26414cd8bfe1",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Compound Boolean expressions can get pretty complex and sometimes are tricky to evaluate. We can use a tool called a truth table to help us evaluate compound Boolean expressions.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Evaluating Expressions",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dab8d54a-d821-4f3d-8b44-26414cd8bfe1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "77b11936-13e6-4543-aed9-412cdaca6e21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5e193446-5b8c-4b32-a0df-6cc3ad2d45e8",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***truth table***."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5e193446-5b8c-4b32-a0df-6cc3ad2d45e8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "77b11936-13e6-4543-aed9-412cdaca6e21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "94240f5e-015b-430b-a8ef-b1286a2d04ce",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Even though compound Boolean expressions can get complex, every compound Boolean expression can be broken down into our three core logical operators: NOT, AND, and OR.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "94240f5e-015b-430b-a8ef-b1286a2d04ce",
        "lesson_activity.key": "77b11936-13e6-4543-aed9-412cdaca6e21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ab81f957-511c-405d-8add-26e92b7548bb",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate the truth table for `A || !B`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***short-circuited evaluation***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Truth Tables handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete the Truth Tables handout.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Truth Tables handout can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of evaluating Boolean expressions using a truth table."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ab81f957-511c-405d-8add-26e92b7548bb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "77b11936-13e6-4543-aed9-412cdaca6e21"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "055ee8a9-47aa-4c1f-a3d6-d4b3ce2573dc",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Today you used AND (`&&`), OR (`||`), and NOT (`!`) to combine conditions. Why might using logical operators be better than writing multiple or nested `if` statements?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should explain that logical operators help simplify code by letting them combine multiple conditions into a single line. This can make programs more readable, less repetitive, and easier to debug. They should also reflect on how logical operators help test combinations of scenarios more efficiently, especially compared to nested conditionals.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "055ee8a9-47aa-4c1f-a3d6-d4b3ce2573dc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "73549527-bc55-40d9-ad8a-c2bf7b88927f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "28a03122-a7ea-405a-9e6f-3730806d4632",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "28a03122-a7ea-405a-9e6f-3730806d4632",
        "lesson_activity.key": "73549527-bc55-40d9-ad8a-c2bf7b88927f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c5fe7756-9e5c-44ef-8808-16218c7c763d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c5fe7756-9e5c-44ef-8808-16218c7c763d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "73549527-bc55-40d9-ad8a-c2bf7b88927f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8249720f-8f40-4579-8d16-297c22b9eb06",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You have learned a lot about logic and software engineering already! Let's take a moment to reflect on and capture what we now know.",
        "name": "Conditions and Logic Review",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8249720f-8f40-4579-8d16-297c22b9eb06",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0d982ba-0e1e-4eec-bac5-84e16d929982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "171feba2-444a-4210-a988-04e708ef0af3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to create a concept map in response to the prompt by brainstorming any concepts and ideas that come to mind.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "A concept map helps students illustrate their understanding of the relationships between the concepts they have learned so far. It usually consists of at least two concepts (nouns), a relationship (verb or short description), and an arrow connecting the concepts. This tool allows students to develop stronger connections with the topic and helps them identify what they know and where gaps might exist.\n\nThere is space on the Unit 4 Guide for students to create their concept maps.\n\nYou can also revisit this to have students continue adding to and revising their concept map."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "171feba2-444a-4210-a988-04e708ef0af3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0d982ba-0e1e-4eec-bac5-84e16d929982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03b35db1-99c4-454e-ac91-fe91697e949c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students review their brainstorm, identify the concepts that are central to the prompt, and draw arrows to connect the concepts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to label the arrows with verbs or short descriptions to identify the relationships between the concepts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students share their concept maps with a neighbor to compare concepts and relationships. Have students add to or revise their concept maps based on their discussions.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The concept map can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the concepts students have learned so far. This can help determine if any concepts need to be revisited or clarified as you begin the lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03b35db1-99c4-454e-ac91-fe91697e949c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0d982ba-0e1e-4eec-bac5-84e16d929982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b2381d55-7667-4bfe-b9a8-eb8b99f76a32",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "De Morgan's Laws"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b2381d55-7667-4bfe-b9a8-eb8b99f76a32",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1502a2b-8334-43d1-8dae-4f7c684897cb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a3702a3b-d902-425e-89b1-2bc6bc4565c8",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "As our Boolean expressions become more complex, we may need to find ways to make them easier to understand and make our programs run more efficiently.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a3702a3b-d902-425e-89b1-2bc6bc4565c8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1502a2b-8334-43d1-8dae-4f7c684897cb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "01e04553-0996-4899-bc50-2e5c6ee2c2da",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate the truth tables for `!(A && B)` and `!A || !B`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How can truth tables help us determine if two Boolean expressions are equivalent?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students realize that since the last column of the truth table shows the resulting Boolean values for the expression, they could compare the last column of both truth tables to check for equivalence.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "01e04553-0996-4899-bc50-2e5c6ee2c2da",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1502a2b-8334-43d1-8dae-4f7c684897cb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cb937c3c-29d0-4189-bf26-a61dc7c5ee47",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***De Morgan's Laws*** and introduce the rules.\n\n**Do This:** Click through the animated slides to demonstrate simplifying the Boolean expressions:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Applying the NOT ( `!` ) to `A`\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Changing the AND ( `&&` ) to OR ( `||` )\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Applying the NOT ( `!` ) to `B`\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Applying the NOT ( `!` ) to `A`\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Changing the AND ( `&&` ) to OR ( `||` )\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Applying the NOT ( `!` ) to `B`\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate how to use truth tables to prove the Boolean expressions `!(A || B)` and `!A && !B` are equivalent."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cb937c3c-29d0-4189-bf26-a61dc7c5ee47",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1502a2b-8334-43d1-8dae-4f7c684897cb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e078f0d0-8024-4aa0-9ce1-f04b9e62c50c",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "De Morgan's Laws can also be applied to Boolean expressions with relational operators.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e078f0d0-8024-4aa0-9ce1-f04b9e62c50c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1502a2b-8334-43d1-8dae-4f7c684897cb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bb3511e4-9c46-4cfe-bcc2-9ff84a2c6d22",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate simplifying Boolean expressions with relational operators.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students predict the result before showing the equivalent expression."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bb3511e4-9c46-4cfe-bcc2-9ff84a2c6d22",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1502a2b-8334-43d1-8dae-4f7c684897cb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fd39a3a9-72ae-44fd-9693-c53838ae43e4",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let's use De Morgan's Laws to practice simplifying Boolean expressions and proving the equivalence of compound Boolean expressions.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Simplifying Boolean Expressions",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fd39a3a9-72ae-44fd-9693-c53838ae43e4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1502a2b-8334-43d1-8dae-4f7c684897cb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6cb5a026-d78b-40f0-bb95-49f77a4cb7d2",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the De Morgan's Laws handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the instructions for the Around the World activity.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "As students work, circulate the room to check that they are successfully following the Around the World steps and are not getting stuck at a station.\n\nAllow pairs who may need more time on each part to complete two stations instead of all four. Students should complete Station A or B AND Station C or D."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6cb5a026-d78b-40f0-bb95-49f77a4cb7d2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1502a2b-8334-43d1-8dae-4f7c684897cb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e85aa732-8a96-40b6-9863-1f67b7db70c6",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Look at your solution for Station A or B. Were the two expressions equivalent? How do you know?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students note that the two expressions were equivalent at both Stations A and B because their resulting truth tables had the same final truth values.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students who did not complete both A and B look at a neighbor’s solution."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e85aa732-8a96-40b6-9863-1f67b7db70c6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1502a2b-8334-43d1-8dae-4f7c684897cb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d47b2801-6a92-46bb-9180-c703405d5dc6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Two software engineers have written two different code segments to solve the same problem. One of the engineers thinks that both code segments are equivalent, but the other engineer thinks that they're not. Let's use what we've learned about De Morgan's Laws and truth tables to help these engineers determine if these two code segments are equivalent!",
        "name": "Solve the Problem",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d47b2801-6a92-46bb-9180-c703405d5dc6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cd7f86ec-457e-46be-a9af-de8cd084c099"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d2a03336-930d-4a4a-a8c7-e1375370d930",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the scenario.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to use De Morgan's Laws to determine if the two code segments are equivalent.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate the solution.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d2a03336-930d-4a4a-a8c7-e1375370d930",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cd7f86ec-457e-46be-a9af-de8cd084c099"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d5f6003c-fda3-4784-ae85-118215a253ff",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d5f6003c-fda3-4784-ae85-118215a253ff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cd7f86ec-457e-46be-a9af-de8cd084c099"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dc99c523-cf8c-40f0-891c-1426eb8d64f8",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dc99c523-cf8c-40f0-891c-1426eb8d64f8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cd7f86ec-457e-46be-a9af-de8cd084c099"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e3c375f4-cb4f-46df-ab26-70e5bed81a0d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *The owner of the Joyful Pastries food truck wants to find all orders with quantities that are multiples of 12. How would we write the condition to find these orders?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest using the mod operator to check if there is a remainder from dividing the quantity by 12. If there is no remainder, they can return that order or add it to an array to keep track of all orders found.",
        "name": "Evenly Divisible",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students guiding questions to help identify using the mod ( `%` ) operator for this condition. For example,\n* *How do we know that a number is a multiple of 12?*\n* *What does it mean for a number to be evenly divisible by another number? Should there be a remainder?*\n* *What could we use to check if a number is evenly divisible by another number?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e3c375f4-cb4f-46df-ab26-70e5bed81a0d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e6ada6a0-248e-425f-bb01-aa74b73cb2e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "eeff6e3c-e959-4a65-9351-c339eddcbf8f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the solution."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "eeff6e3c-e959-4a65-9351-c339eddcbf8f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e6ada6a0-248e-425f-bb01-aa74b73cb2e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ed1a2b5b-9bd2-493e-8c8c-c6295ac90a86",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ed1a2b5b-9bd2-493e-8c8c-c6295ac90a86",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318885b0-aecb-4c8a-8ee2-c175c9d6cac3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "02f146cd-a211-4055-a4d1-b96844f01540",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned how to use one-way and two-way selection statements, nested conditional statements, and logical operators to test one or more conditions. Today, we're going to explore another way that we can test multiple conditions in our programs.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "02f146cd-a211-4055-a4d1-b96844f01540",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318885b0-aecb-4c8a-8ee2-c175c9d6cac3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3b140249-ba61-4cd3-a9a9-46fc9e696e12",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Multi-Selection Statements"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3b140249-ba61-4cd3-a9a9-46fc9e696e12",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318885b0-aecb-4c8a-8ee2-c175c9d6cac3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "64d251da-b6b3-4dde-b19d-fcb9c720a2a4",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the code segment includes an `else-if` branch that checks an additional condition and executes its block of code when that condition is `true`. Students may wonder how this is similar and different from using nested `if` statements and logical operators."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "64d251da-b6b3-4dde-b19d-fcb9c720a2a4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318885b0-aecb-4c8a-8ee2-c175c9d6cac3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f116ffd1-d487-433e-a487-7d4177030ffc",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned different ways to expand the capabilities of conditionals to check multiple conditions throughout this unit. We know how to use one-way and two-way selection statements to decide what code to execute based on the result of a condition. We can also use multi-selection statements to check multiple conditions.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Multi-Selection Statements",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f116ffd1-d487-433e-a487-7d4177030ffc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318885b0-aecb-4c8a-8ee2-c175c9d6cac3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ba23288d-bb47-4f76-aeba-37a14af4990d",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Multi-Selection Statements"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ba23288d-bb47-4f76-aeba-37a14af4990d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318885b0-aecb-4c8a-8ee2-c175c9d6cac3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d5e4823b-c231-43df-adeb-86d14fdb63e4",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Multi-Selection Statements*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d5e4823b-c231-43df-adeb-86d14fdb63e4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318885b0-aecb-4c8a-8ee2-c175c9d6cac3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4fe063a7-08db-434b-b90d-966621c1e172",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***multi-selection statement***.\n\n**Do This:** Explain the flowchart for a multi-selection statement:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Explain each branch of the flowchart\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> If the condition is `false`, we move to the next condition\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> If the condition is `true`, its task is execute"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4fe063a7-08db-434b-b90d-966621c1e172",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318885b0-aecb-4c8a-8ee2-c175c9d6cac3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a43a910-7d77-469b-a358-5bd91a8f36a2",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "At the beginning of the lesson, we discussed using the mod operator to check if a value is evenly divisible by another value. This algorithm is useful for various scenarios, including analyzing data to find patterns and information.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Practice",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a43a910-7d77-469b-a358-5bd91a8f36a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318885b0-aecb-4c8a-8ee2-c175c9d6cac3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "76b90c3f-d4c6-41fe-9bb4-92c303357e23",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Writing Algorithms handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to work with their partner to write pseudocode for one of the problems.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You can also have students draw a flowchart to illustrate their algorithm in addition to or instead of writing pseudocode."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "76b90c3f-d4c6-41fe-9bb4-92c303357e23",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318885b0-aecb-4c8a-8ee2-c175c9d6cac3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0016108b-4f04-477b-b54d-7c919038bed0",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5 and 6. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to Level 6 to implement their algorithm.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Multi-Selection Statements",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of evaluating code segments using multi-selection statements.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of writing algorithms using multi-selection statements."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0016108b-4f04-477b-b54d-7c919038bed0",
