    {
      "key": "071efc84-1c1c-4b70-b196-6740260d6a21",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Think of something you've done where you had to repeat the same action over and over . . . maybe a chore, a warm-up drill, or something in a game. What was it? How did you keep track of how many times you had done it?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recognize that many tasks involve repeating actions a known number of times and that they often use counters (e.g., tally marks, scoreboards, timer apps). This prepares them to understand why `for` loops are useful in programming: they automate repetition when the number of iterations is known."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "071efc84-1c1c-4b70-b196-6740260d6a21",
        "lesson_activity.key": "690b631c-26f6-4826-9371-82327f7a3ee1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "92169742-1b29-4245-aa8c-73734f8143e0",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "92169742-1b29-4245-aa8c-73734f8143e0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "afe8090a-3c56-459e-8959-a27639540702"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "988a99ee-f103-4116-9c72-edc0d431fc41",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We previously learned how to traverse a 1D array using a `while` loop so we could access or modify all of its elements. Java also gives us another way to repeat a block of code or traverse a 1D array.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "988a99ee-f103-4116-9c72-edc0d431fc41",
        "lesson_activity.key": "afe8090a-3c56-459e-8959-a27639540702"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6591d4aa-6f85-4b9d-9b33-c5e3fadac61c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: For Loops"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6591d4aa-6f85-4b9d-9b33-c5e3fadac61c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "afe8090a-3c56-459e-8959-a27639540702"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a469b52-ab03-4cfd-9427-8801e6ae398c",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice the syntax and functionality of the `for` loop in the program to repeat a block of code. Students might also notice similarities and differences between a `while` loop and the `for` loop and suggest benefits of using a `for` loop. Students may wonder why they might use a `for` loop instead of a `while` loop."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a469b52-ab03-4cfd-9427-8801e6ae398c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "afe8090a-3c56-459e-8959-a27639540702"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d047845c-d9c2-49d7-9542-888b0349396d",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this program, we see an example of a `for` loop that can repeat a block of code. We often can use either a `while` loop or a `for` loop interchangeably, however there are some cases where a `for` loop might be easier to work with for a problem than a `while` loop.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "For Loops",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d047845c-d9c2-49d7-9542-888b0349396d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "afe8090a-3c56-459e-8959-a27639540702"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4db30cf1-562d-40e5-9ebc-858ac427a916",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *For Loops*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4db30cf1-562d-40e5-9ebc-858ac427a916",
        "lesson_activity.key": "afe8090a-3c56-459e-8959-a27639540702"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "47575836-8c4b-40b1-9af3-4e77138eb444",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: For Loops"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "47575836-8c4b-40b1-9af3-4e77138eb444",
        "lesson_activity.key": "afe8090a-3c56-459e-8959-a27639540702"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bd9e157e-45f8-4687-9905-96b075e4d7f0",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n**Do This:** Explain the components of a `for` loop:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***loop control variable***\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The condition that must be `true` to continue the loop\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The change of the loop control variable\n\n**Do This:** Explain the functionality of the increment and decrement operators:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***increment*** and introduce the increment operator\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Define ***decrement*** and introduce the decrement operator"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bd9e157e-45f8-4687-9905-96b075e4d7f0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "afe8090a-3c56-459e-8959-a27639540702"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "122558ee-6833-45ed-9370-5d8c43caeee3",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate tracing a `for` loop.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Tracing Loops",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Model tracing the first two iterations of the loop, then ask students to assist in completing the rest of the trace table."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "122558ee-6833-45ed-9370-5d8c43caeee3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "afe8090a-3c56-459e-8959-a27639540702"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "27d09191-a7c9-4fb1-ab1f-ff0cacb9482f",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Define ***off-by-one error***:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Introduce the error\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Explain the cause of the error\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Explain possible solutions to fix the error",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students trace the code segment to identify the error before explaining the off-by-one error. You can also have students suggest solutions to fix the error before discussing the possible solutions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "27d09191-a7c9-4fb1-ab1f-ff0cacb9482f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "afe8090a-3c56-459e-8959-a27639540702"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d18ff060-77b9-4a9d-9607-4c4c86e14660",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5 and 6. Students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to Level 6 to complete a choice level to traverse a 1D array using a `for` loop in the console or The Neighborhood.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Using for Loops",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the key terms and traversing 1D arrays using a `for` loop."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d18ff060-77b9-4a9d-9607-4c4c86e14660",
        "lesson_activity.key": "afe8090a-3c56-459e-8959-a27639540702"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fbc4d308-6447-444f-95f2-92cab75ccb0a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned a lot about `while` loops and `for` loops and how these loops are interchangeable. Depending on the problem we are trying to solve, we might choose to use one type of loop over another.",
        "name": "Design Thinking",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fbc4d308-6447-444f-95f2-92cab75ccb0a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "039015a6-817e-4392-bbb0-df2b4264c981"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f6758afe-593c-4d08-86a5-d29fcf3a3b0d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which type of loop would be best for this scenario? Why?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest using a `while` loop because this problem does not have a value that can be used as a loop control variable. Students realize that a `while` loop might be more ideal for this type of scenario because they are unsure how many times the loop might need to repeat.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which type of loop would be best for this scenario? Why?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest using a `for` loop because this problem has a value that can be used as a loop control variable. Students realize that a `for` loop might be more ideal for this type of scenario because they can determine how many times the loop needs to repeat.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f6758afe-593c-4d08-86a5-d29fcf3a3b0d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "039015a6-817e-4392-bbb0-df2b4264c981"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ba963308-e033-4fd1-9ae0-8657cf7faab4",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ba963308-e033-4fd1-9ae0-8657cf7faab4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "039015a6-817e-4392-bbb0-df2b4264c981"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "60a8d939-feb1-4ee7-bc8c-938940ae1762",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "60a8d939-feb1-4ee7-bc8c-938940ae1762",
        "lesson_activity.key": "039015a6-817e-4392-bbb0-df2b4264c981"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f0ce0e4-2521-4e62-9703-e53ee7cda111",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You all have used search engines like Google before. These search engines use a technology called “Natural Language Processing,” or NLP for short, to return relevant results. NLP helps the search engine determine, no matter how your words are spelled or combined, what helpful information should be surfaced.",
        "name": "Search Engines",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f0ce0e4-2521-4e62-9703-e53ee7cda111",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b2acd0d8-6bf7-4521-aa81-61c727a1785d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "075771ec-a749-4726-bb10-6abff8ef119f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When we use search engines like Google, they use Natural Language Processing to return relevant results. How do they know what we are looking for?  How might algorithms to identify key words or phrases in our searches work?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that search engines are able to parse the text of what has been searched for in order to extract keywords or phrases. Students should offer suggestions for how a keyword or phrase is found, such as looping through each word in the search query.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class.\n\nYou can also ask students additional guiding questions to help them realize that smart assistants are identifying keywords and how they might do this. For example:\n* *If you tell Siri to send a message to your friend, how does it know that you want to send a message? How does it know who to send it to? What about what the message itself should be?*\n* *How do you think it breaks up your question or statement to find these pieces?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "075771ec-a749-4726-bb10-6abff8ef119f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b2acd0d8-6bf7-4521-aa81-61c727a1785d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6f7ce585-4932-40fc-9d4b-db4716af64ac",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6f7ce585-4932-40fc-9d4b-db4716af64ac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30ffdf54-88e1-4b83-9c9a-c8c1f0558747"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7df6ca9e-ce8b-40e0-9a58-3d60ef6770dc",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You’ve seen `String` objects in the past. Today, we will learn about the `substring()` method in the `String` class, and how that method can be used in a variety of standard `String` algorithms. ",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7df6ca9e-ce8b-40e0-9a58-3d60ef6770dc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30ffdf54-88e1-4b83-9c9a-c8c1f0558747"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "789e6e04-434f-4e86-a186-f4d6a0610ef0",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: A Standard String Algorithm"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "789e6e04-434f-4e86-a186-f4d6a0610ef0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30ffdf54-88e1-4b83-9c9a-c8c1f0558747"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9a39fe8b-353c-4be1-aa7e-97ff42985024",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should notice that the program iterates through the characters of a `String` using a `for` loop. This should lead to a discussion about what the `String` variable `forward` looks like at the end of the loop. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9a39fe8b-353c-4be1-aa7e-97ff42985024",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30ffdf54-88e1-4b83-9c9a-c8c1f0558747"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "13c13eaa-bce4-44dd-b6a6-51e8a5abfa6b",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What is the difference between the way the substring() method is used in each line?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should recall that the substring() method can get the characters between a starting and ending index in a String object or from a starting index to the end of the String object.\n",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Reversing a String"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "13c13eaa-bce4-44dd-b6a6-51e8a5abfa6b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30ffdf54-88e1-4b83-9c9a-c8c1f0558747"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "37e6c276-8de5-4f4f-bcf2-0fd44aa28a32",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we use the `substring()` method, we can get the characters between a starting and ending index in a `String` object or from a starting index to the end of the `String` object.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "37e6c276-8de5-4f4f-bcf2-0fd44aa28a32",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30ffdf54-88e1-4b83-9c9a-c8c1f0558747"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dfc2bffd-483f-4247-84ca-5cdc98206e3a",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n\n- *What is the purpose of the `current` variable in this code?*\n- *What happens to the `forward` variable each time the loop executes?*\n- *What modifications would you need to make to print the `palindrome` variable backward?*\n\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that the current variable is “looking at” a single character each time the loop iterates. This should allow them to build the forward variable piece by piece and see that the word is being “constructed”. This should lead students to speculate about how one might build the string backwards. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "In the next few Investigate and Modify levels, students will walk through, step by step, how to “construct” the palindrome backwards, so it is okay if they don’t land on the “correct” algorithm in this discussion. Instead, use this as an opportunity to celebrate critical thinking and problem solving skills, and encourage many different ideas. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dfc2bffd-483f-4247-84ca-5cdc98206e3a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30ffdf54-88e1-4b83-9c9a-c8c1f0558747"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8cd08ddc-add2-4800-b28d-4bc8aba47571",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Reversing a String"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8cd08ddc-add2-4800-b28d-4bc8aba47571",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30ffdf54-88e1-4b83-9c9a-c8c1f0558747"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3d0f2ea4-8563-49d3-9fca-728c67704c37",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3d0f2ea4-8563-49d3-9fca-728c67704c37",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30ffdf54-88e1-4b83-9c9a-c8c1f0558747"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ffd265eb-b0d4-4374-a0d7-f354d7235991",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5 and 6. Students complete a choice level on Level 5 to practice using the `substring()` method to find if one or more `substrings` have a particular property. On Level 6, students complete a choice level using the substring() method and conditional expressions to determine the number of substrings that meet specific criteria. \n",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Implementing String Algorithms",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Implementing String Algorithms"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ffd265eb-b0d4-4374-a0d7-f354d7235991",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30ffdf54-88e1-4b83-9c9a-c8c1f0558747"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f919d995-95f6-4dce-a808-eadaa225ba0e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How can the standard algorithms we learned about today be applied to search engine results to improve functionality and provide more relevant results to users?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should begin brainstorming and suggesting ideas about applying the algorithms they learned in today’s lesson in order to improve the functionality of search engine results. ",
        "name": "Implementing String Algorithms"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f919d995-95f6-4dce-a808-eadaa225ba0e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "924618cf-1878-4c72-b679-38d4b951e6ab"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a9aa3d13-e69a-4aa8-af1e-fbf029ca18b4",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How might we use methods in the `String` class to analyze text and data in our upcoming project?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students will likely have several different ideas for using these methods, such as using the `indexOf()` and `substring()` methods to break a sentence up into words or using the `indexOf()` method to check if a sentence or phrase contains specific characters and provide a response based on the result."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a9aa3d13-e69a-4aa8-af1e-fbf029ca18b4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "924618cf-1878-4c72-b679-38d4b951e6ab"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "73033c61-dfe4-4dd6-b8f4-55a2138ab917",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "73033c61-dfe4-4dd6-b8f4-55a2138ab917",
        "lesson_activity.key": "924618cf-1878-4c72-b679-38d4b951e6ab"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f583f580-de56-4e01-a1f9-e8dda75adbcc",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You’ve all probably seen the hands moving on a clock, but have you ever stopped to consider how you might use a loop to simulate moving these clock hands in Java?",
        "name": "Clock Hands",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f583f580-de56-4e01-a1f9-e8dda75adbcc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3b26df7-5f91-4777-96de-441e89dfe5ea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d2c728c7-04bf-46da-a87a-d08c268244ee",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How many times did the second hand “tick” before the minute hand “ticked”? \nHow could you use iteration statements to represent the ticking of a clock?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that two loops, one for the ticking of the minutes and one for the ticking of the seconds, would be required.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students will likely have varying comfort levels with constructing these for loops prior to the lesson. Teachers should celebrate a wide variety of ideas and not linger overlong on this warm up. This will ensure that the problem-solving and prior knowledge of some students is honored, but that all students are given the opportunity to move up to speed. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d2c728c7-04bf-46da-a87a-d08c268244ee",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3b26df7-5f91-4777-96de-441e89dfe5ea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "36333079-fe92-473e-a65a-49616fbdb777",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "36333079-fe92-473e-a65a-49616fbdb777",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b1fc14c7-3116-4a8c-8422-5234e909e7c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6b201dee-b197-4e46-aeb4-030660977c3e",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we have explored nested loops using the hands of a clock, let’s see other ways we can apply nested loops to Java programs. ",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Nested Loops",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6b201dee-b197-4e46-aeb4-030660977c3e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b1fc14c7-3116-4a8c-8422-5234e909e7c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6b0d832d-16d5-41c1-9eb4-25c11c935657",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.*\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recognize the nested loops allow them to simulate the same clock movements they explored in the warm up. They should notice the different variables used in the loop headers and discuss the roles each variable plays in the program."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6b0d832d-16d5-41c1-9eb4-25c11c935657",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b1fc14c7-3116-4a8c-8422-5234e909e7c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fb96d90b-6c4d-4054-a476-fe76ac91c651",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video - *Nested Loops.*",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the Guide to Curriculum Videos."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fb96d90b-6c4d-4054-a476-fe76ac91c651",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b1fc14c7-3116-4a8c-8422-5234e909e7c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dd6f4653-0f58-42bb-a8e5-fb384f9e68c2",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Nested loops are like building blocks in programming, letting us create complex patterns by repeating actions within each other. Just like laying bricks to form a wall, nested loops offer a structured approach to handling repetitive tasks. Let’s look more carefully at the syntax and logic for using nested loops. ",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Syntax and Logic",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dd6f4653-0f58-42bb-a8e5-fb384f9e68c2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b1fc14c7-3116-4a8c-8422-5234e909e7c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f8b2cf9e-0387-4fe6-bd2a-918fd28a09c4",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2 and 3. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate & Modify: Nested Iteration"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f8b2cf9e-0387-4fe6-bd2a-918fd28a09c4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b1fc14c7-3116-4a8c-8422-5234e909e7c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d97a2498-4fde-4c5d-b00a-109cb7c68bbb",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Define nested loop and explain that when a loop is nested inside another loop, the inner loop must complete all its iterations before the outer loop can continue.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Click through the animated slide to demonstrate tracing a nested loop.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Model tracing the first two iterations of the loop, then ask students to assist in completing the rest of the trace table."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d97a2498-4fde-4c5d-b00a-109cb7c68bbb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b1fc14c7-3116-4a8c-8422-5234e909e7c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "edcb30b0-8ce4-40e3-b805-febfb4e5a39e",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Have students trace the code segment.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Click through the animated slide to explain the solution.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "edcb30b0-8ce4-40e3-b805-febfb4e5a39e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b1fc14c7-3116-4a8c-8422-5234e909e7c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "442ebac4-f0cb-4157-8b4f-2ede865bfdf9",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now we know how to handle two important parts of using nested iteration in a Java program — the syntax for the loops and the way trace tables are used to check the logic of those loops. These are both important steps in helping us use nested iteration successfully.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Nested Iteration",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Nested Iteration",
        "remarks": true,
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice levels can be used as formative assessments to gauge understanding of tracing and writing nested loops."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "442ebac4-f0cb-4157-8b4f-2ede865bfdf9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b1fc14c7-3116-4a8c-8422-5234e909e7c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f1f24207-d1cb-4f9f-a9ac-188bc8cb9fe5",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software engineers use nested loops to solve a wide variety of problems. Many of these problems use the same types of loops we wrote today. We have done a lot today to grow our programming abilities!",
        "name": "Three W’s",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f1f24207-d1cb-4f9f-a9ac-188bc8cb9fe5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9e7803f6-710f-426c-849b-b6fb6eb05ea9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "88c8051b-00ae-4df8-920f-b573b1a79776",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n\n* *What did we learn today?*\n* *So what?*\n* *Now what?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students highlight the concepts and syntax they learned in this lesson, such as how a nested `for` loop can be used to repeat a series of actions within other actions. They should realizedd that nested `for` loops can be used for tasks that are highly repetitive. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the question of the day\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "88c8051b-00ae-4df8-920f-b573b1a79776",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9e7803f6-710f-426c-849b-b6fb6eb05ea9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "77212231-0dda-462a-a781-a265eae98f1b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.\n",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "77212231-0dda-462a-a781-a265eae98f1b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9e7803f6-710f-426c-849b-b6fb6eb05ea9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7fb00bec-42a1-465b-9ac8-f0aca77b26b9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned that tracing is the process of reading through code line by line while keeping track of the variables and their values. When we trace code, we understand exactly what is happening in the program. This technique is very valuable for debugging because it helps us identify where the code may not be behaving as expected.\n\nInformal runtime analysis involves examining the execution of a program in a non-rigorous manner, often by tracing. This helps us get a sense of how the program performs and where potential issues might lie.",
        "name": "Statement Execution Counts",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7fb00bec-42a1-465b-9ac8-f0aca77b26b9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cfd0a8d2-8fef-4fa0-b88e-0283bfaee78f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f7eba399-d4a4-4814-84ea-b53cf114dca6",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Show the sample code on the slide and ask students to review statement 1 and statement 2.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you notice about the number of times each statement executes? What do you notice about the total number of times the program statements execute?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students gain an introductory understanding of informal runtime analysis by observing and discussing the frequency of statement execution in a program. They will analyze the number of times each statement executes and consider the total number of executions for all program statements. Through this discussion, students will develop their skills in tracing code and gain insights into informal runtime analysis."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f7eba399-d4a4-4814-84ea-b53cf114dca6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cfd0a8d2-8fef-4fa0-b88e-0283bfaee78f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cb766d6a-0fc9-4c39-9987-004d5c01296b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cb766d6a-0fc9-4c39-9987-004d5c01296b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "70fec001-954b-4136-872e-5aa6d482d2c8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d76d50b5-046c-487f-b2e4-4b15ca1e1c77",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned how to read through code line by line, keeping track of variables and their values to understand what is happening in a program. Today, we are going to take this a step further by exploring how to determine the number of times a specific statement is executed within a loop. By the end of today's lesson, you will be able to trace through a program, identify the number of times each statement is executed, and conduct informal runtime analyses.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d76d50b5-046c-487f-b2e4-4b15ca1e1c77",
        "lesson_activity.key": "70fec001-954b-4136-872e-5aa6d482d2c8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66d18023-9ce8-4226-bf46-89773bbb78d7",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict: Informal Run-Time Analysis"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66d18023-9ce8-4226-bf46-89773bbb78d7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "70fec001-954b-4136-872e-5aa6d482d2c8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2148a849-ee2d-4e4c-a440-897fd87573f1",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should identify the nested loops from the warm up and share ideas about what each loop controls. Students should also identify the different values used in the loop headers. Students might wonder about the way to count how many times each loop executes, or what The Neighborhood will look like when the program completes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the first step to determining statement execution counts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the second step to determining statement execution counts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review statement execution count and informal run-time analysis.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Discuss the ways that determining statement execution counts may not always be straightforward. What are some things that might add complexity to determining the statement execution count of a loop?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students might mention the various ways a loop header can be modified, adding complexity to determining the statement execution count. Some students may mention changing the loop control variable’s starting value. Others might note that the conditional expression may be altered. Others still may add the different ways the loop control variable may be incremented."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2148a849-ee2d-4e4c-a440-897fd87573f1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "70fec001-954b-4136-872e-5aa6d482d2c8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e27a702a-c59b-47b5-995d-f698fe1aa089",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We now have a basic understanding of how to determine the number of times statements within loops, and nested loops, will execute. This next activity will give you a chance to practice and develop your skills in quickly and efficiently determining statement execution count using code segments similar to those that appear on the AP CS A exam. ",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Partner Practice",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e27a702a-c59b-47b5-995d-f698fe1aa089",
        "lesson_activity.key": "70fec001-954b-4136-872e-5aa6d482d2c8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "627b7f91-6762-4f1e-a80f-d1b7d6121c37",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student an Informal Runtime Analysis practice card.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to find a partner, and assign themselves the role of Partner A or Partner B. Students should then take turns solving each other’s question before swapping cards and finding a new partner. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Determining statement execution counts is not always straightforward, but there are some patterns we can use. What patterns did you notice when you were solving the practice problems?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** This discussion should elicit a variety of responses. Students may notice that it is important to carefully watch how many times each level of the nested loop will iterate. Others may point out that the total number of executions is equal to the product of the number of executions of the inner loop and outer loop. Still more may point out that oftentimes the boundaries of the loop, such as the starting point, ending condition, and step value, can make problems more complex."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "627b7f91-6762-4f1e-a80f-d1b7d6121c37",
        "lesson_activity.key": "70fec001-954b-4136-872e-5aa6d482d2c8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fdc65618-44ca-4a2c-a67b-03973dc19e82",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We now know how to trace code segments in order to determine statement execution counts and conduct informal runtime analysis. With this knowledge, we can begin to optimize our code and make it more efficient. ",
        "name": "Three W's",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fdc65618-44ca-4a2c-a67b-03973dc19e82",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b63222d1-8d73-4f58-b55b-30f46f7b6465"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5cc5df45-fc87-4361-8dc8-cc87e5832fe3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did we learn today?*\n* *So what?*\n* *Now what?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students highlight a variety of strategies for conducting informal loop analysis. Students also recognize that informal loop analysis can help optimize their code in order to make it more efficient. They should also realize that they are now prepared to tackle similar types of multiple choice questions on the AP CS A exam.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5cc5df45-fc87-4361-8dc8-cc87e5832fe3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b63222d1-8d73-4f58-b55b-30f46f7b6465"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4539fe34-37c0-4953-8ed8-08dcd3b90967",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Note:** The unit assessment project is adapted from the Unit 8 project in the Objects First version of the course. As such, there are criteria contained within the rubric that might not align with the current level of knowledge of students. You are encouraged to create a version of the rubric which you feel is fair for your students, given their trajectory within the CED-aligned version of the course.\n\nStudents work on the project throughout the unit to brainstorm, plan, and begin developing their program. Students then have three dedicated class periods to refine and complete their projects.\n\nIf there is not enough time for the three-day project, a one-day option achieves the targeted learning objectives and goals. If using this option, refer to the [**Creative Coding with the Console Project 1-Day Lesson Plan**](https://studio.code.org/s/csa8-2023/lessons/13). While the one-day option covers the learning objectives and goals, it shortens planning and reflection time. Consider this tradeoff when deciding which version to use."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4539fe34-37c0-4953-8ed8-08dcd3b90967",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c2cc4a70-c7c2-4add-8458-fed67dcc5a63"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6225f7f2-650d-4a95-a1d5-6a8834fe7686",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Before working towards your final benchmark, review the project requirements and rubric and evaluate your progress. Self-assessing your progress will help you identify which tasks to focus on during your project workdays.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Warm Up",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6225f7f2-650d-4a95-a1d5-6a8834fe7686",
        "lesson_activity.key": "01253509-d814-4685-b97a-ca13ae55f670"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d16bf93b-817f-4846-bcef-23296f64c8f7",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students individually self-assess their project using the rubric on the last page of the Creative Coding with the Console Project Planning Guide and review any remaining questions in the \"Need to Know\" column on page two.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What questions do you still have that need answering for this project?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share any questions they still have in their \"Need to Know\" column.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class.\n\nStudents may have questions that are unrelated or beyond the scope of the project. Encourage students to research these questions as extension activities. Focus this discussion on answering questions specific to the content covered in this unit and for the project."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d16bf93b-817f-4846-bcef-23296f64c8f7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "01253509-d814-4685-b97a-ca13ae55f670"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dfebd083-6a7e-4544-8c78-c391b01c450a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students post tasks they want to complete for the third benchmark in the \"To Do\" column of their Project Planning Board."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dfebd083-6a7e-4544-8c78-c391b01c450a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "01253509-d814-4685-b97a-ca13ae55f670"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "22dac996-2d17-432d-9fad-d699f32c33bc",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Using the remaining items on your Project Planning Board and the feedback from your peers, continue to develop your Creative Coding Project. Each time you complete a goal, commit your code and move the tasks to the next column. There should only be one item in the “In Progress” column at a time, meaning that each item should be entirely completed before moving on to the next item.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Development",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "22dac996-2d17-432d-9fad-d699f32c33bc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "01253509-d814-4685-b97a-ca13ae55f670"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1a6d9038-c397-4503-b7d0-f8558c53d8ec",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students prioritize the remaining tasks on their Project Planning Board based on feedback and self-assessment.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to work on the Creative Coding with the Console Project.",
        "progression_name": "Creative Coding with the Console Project",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Remind students to refer to their Project Planning Board to decide what tasks to work on during this time. You can also encourage students to request a code review from their peers as they work."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1a6d9038-c397-4503-b7d0-f8558c53d8ec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "01253509-d814-4685-b97a-ca13ae55f670"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "131a534d-137c-4b87-9eef-e8a310c05cd7",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You wrote acceptance criteria for your previous Creative Coding Project's user stories to define when each user story can be considered complete. With these, you were able to conduct acceptance testing to determine which of your user stories are complete and which ones still need work.",
        "name": "Acceptance Testing",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "131a534d-137c-4b87-9eef-e8a310c05cd7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "01253509-d814-4685-b97a-ca13ae55f670"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bd5f5302-14f7-4675-b83d-7c36d5a7e358",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to review acceptance testing."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bd5f5302-14f7-4675-b83d-7c36d5a7e358",
        "lesson_activity.key": "01253509-d814-4685-b97a-ca13ae55f670"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fd7fa6d0-1c35-4523-bcd7-334ca299d334",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let's write and test acceptance criteria for your user stories. Your reviewer should test your program and determine which of your user stories are complete and which ones still need work.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fd7fa6d0-1c35-4523-bcd7-334ca299d334",
        "lesson_activity.key": "01253509-d814-4685-b97a-ca13ae55f670"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a8148b39-e1af-48d0-9758-69e9cdd7362e",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to have students participate in the Code Review Call and Response.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to conduct a code review on their Creative Coding with the Console Project. Have students write a code review request that includes acceptance criteria for their user stories. Afterward, students review their peer’s code and determine if the acceptance criteria are met.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students may be at different points when it is time for the code review. Emphasize to students that their work does not need to be completed to get feedback. Remind students that the problem-solving and development process is iterative and that receiving feedback from peers while they are working can help give them additional insights, perspectives, and guidance."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a8148b39-e1af-48d0-9758-69e9cdd7362e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "01253509-d814-4685-b97a-ca13ae55f670"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8c5b4fa8-3fd9-4b42-aa38-4ea464a7fd0b",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students update their Project Planning Board with any tasks they completed, changed, or added.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Wrap Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "You can review the Project Planning Board as an optional completion assessment."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8c5b4fa8-3fd9-4b42-aa38-4ea464a7fd0b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "01253509-d814-4685-b97a-ca13ae55f670"
      }
